entry.title: [a11y] EnableAccessibility should be a no-op if a11y is already enabled.
entry.content:
BrowserAccessibilityStateImpl::EnableAccessibility should not do any

work if a11y is already enabled.



On Mac, accessibilitySetValue can cause us to call EnableAccessibility

multiple times, causing the web contents to churn their tree if a11y

is already enabled. With the "Hover Text" feature on Mac, this caused

us to be constantly giving the feature a new tree, seemingly confusing

it and causing it to not show the text as expected. On larger sites I

was even able to reproduce a hang in some cases due to the size of the

tree being serialized.



This change simply checks to see if a11y is already enabled when

EnableAccessibility is called, and if so, we don't do any additional

work.



Fixed: 1513295

entry.title: Make ComputedStyle subgroups use compressed Members.

reduced the number of DataRef operations we need to make (due to memory

performance hit. (Performance is even a tiny bit better, although there

entry.title: Clone and update multicol fragments properly when adding OOFs.
entry.content:
If the original inner multicol container had descendant multicols with

pending OOFs, make sure that the cloned and updated multicol also

reflects this state.



For that to work, we also need to allow more OOF descendant propagation

when cloning and updating fragmentainers via SimplifiedLayoutAlgorithm.

Remove the disable_oof_descendants_propagation_ flag, and instead block

such propagation for OOF fragments that are inside a fragmentainer. Such

fragments are special, and the propagation is handled manually in

OutOfFlowLayoutPart::AddOOFToFragmentainer(). All other fragments should

propagate normally.



The problem here was that the HasNestedMulticolsWithOOFs() flag in

PhysicalFragment got lost when the fragments got cloned and updated, which in turn prevented us from missing the cache in

LayoutBox::CachedLayoutResult() when re-laying out.

entry.title: [BRP] Fix OOB poison tests
entry.content:
Several tests would fail when backup_ref_ptr_poison_oob_ptr is true.



Other than the obvious AllowPtrArithmetic, there were a couple less

trivial issues:

- raw_ptr needs to be zero'ed or destructed before freeing memory to

avoid triggering Dangling Pointer Detector

- CountingRawPtr is no longer backed by BRP implementation, so OOB

protection won't kick in

- A bug in BackupRefPtrTest.Advance has been fixed to correctly test

larger sizes, so a hardcoded array no longer cuts it

- volatile is needed to avoid optimizing out dereferences (std::ignore

is enough if the code triggers CHECK)

entry.title: [Office upload] Handle escape key as a "cancel" in File Handler dialog
entry.content:
Handle the escape keydown event as a "cancel" user choice in the File

Handler dialog.



Previously, an escape keydown event would close all office upload

dialogs, except for the OneDrive setup dialog, with an empty user choice

since CloudUploadDialog::ShouldCloseDialogOnEscape() was true.



This led to weird metric results as an empty user choice (which is never

expected) would be recorded and mistakenly translated to the user

choosing an invalid local file task.



Update the code so that an escape in the File Handler dialog will

correctly be recorded as a "cancel" user choice.



Add keydown event listeners on the document in connectedCallback() and

explicitly remove them in disconnectedCallback(). They have to be

removed as otherwise they will be called upon keydown events after they

have been removed from the DOM.

entry.title: on-device: adds support for redacting/rejecting text
entry.content:
Three behaviors are supported:

. Rejection, which stops execution.

. Text is redacted if it matches a regex.

. Text is redacted if it matches a regex and does not occur in the

input text.



For the third-case I need the ability to get the string the user

entered. I used ProtoField for this. As for compose we have multiple

permutations (rewrite vs generate) I used repeated ProtoField. The

code returns the first non-empty string found that matches one of

the ProtoFields.



This also adds an enum for those regexs that will need special

processing, but they aren't wired up yet.

entry.title: [AsyncSB] Use AsyncCheckTracker to determine if main page load is blocked.
entry.content:
When SafeBrowsingAsyncRealTimeCheck is enabled, whether the main page

load is blocked cannot be determined solely by is_subresource and

threat_type, because the page load is no longer blocked by the check

deterministically. Going forward, AsyncCheckTracker will be

responsible for monitoring the status of the navigation and inform

whether the main page load is blocked. The old function is renamed

to IsMainPageLoadPendingWithSyncCheck so it is clear that it only

works when async check is disabled.



To replace all current usage of UnsafeResource::IsMainPageLoadBlocked

with AsyncCheckTracker::IsMainPageLoadPending, this CL makes the

following changes to avoid dependency issue:

* unsafe_resource_util is bubbled up from security_interstitials/ to

safe_browsing/ so it can depend on AsyncCheckTracker.

* The client_report_util target is merged into its parent browser

target to avoid circular dependency.



Also avoid using the word "blocked" going forward, since it can also

mean this URL is dangerous so it is "blocked" by Safe Browsing,

whereas here it means the navigation is "blocked" because the check

has not yet completed. Therefore, IsMainPageLoadBlocked is renamed to

IsMainPageLoadPending.



There is no behavioral change in this CL. The actual implementation of

AsyncCheckTracker::IsMainPageLoadPending will be done in a follow up CL.

entry.title: RTCVDAdapter: Fallback due to small resolution in media thread
entry.content:
WebRTC video decoder fallbacks a hardware decoder to a software

decoder when the number of the hardware decoders is more than 8 and

the resolution is less than 320x240 on non ChromeOS. The resolution

of a frame is detected when the frame is decoded. Therefore the

fallback due to the low resolution is reported in the second frame.

The second frame is not keyframe and thus it is necessary to request

a keyframe to an sender side. This increases the start up time in a

webrtc video call.

To resolve the issue, we would rather check the resolution in webrtc

decoder thread before decoding by parsing the stream.

Libgav1 is newly built on Android to parse av1 stream. This increases

the chrome binary size by 41283 bytes.

entry.title: Workaround Max Texture Size on Android
entry.content:
If the runtime gives us a recommendedImageRectWidth that is greater than

2048, then we will exceed the max texture size of 4096, and then cause

rendering artifacts, because a single eye will cover more than half of

the texture. This change patches the issue by allocating equal space to

each item in an `OpenXrViewConfiguration` class on Android while leaving

Windows alone.



Future work will investigate more robust ways of calculating/retrieving

this max size, and/or even removing this requirement all together.



This max size is specified at:

https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:third_party/angle/src/libANGLE/renderer/gl/renderergl_utils.cpp;l=2365;drc=edcfab40c5262714b2735c7c8dcfc0d185ee9997

entry.title: bind_internal.h cleanup: Guard remaining static_asserts.
entry.content:
Most existing static_asserts have already been guarded using the

"assert inside lambda inside templated struct inside std::conjunction"

trick already documented in bind.h. However, three asserts that

indicated Bind misuse (as opposed to invariants inside the Bind

machinery) had not been so guarded, and I tripped over some of them

while trying to refactor. So guard them too.



The net effect is that Yet More Cases of misuse will only print one

failing static_assert and no further compiler errors. This also ensures

the result of BindOnce()/BindRepeating() is always a

BindFailedCheckPreviousErrors in such cases, instead of often being

void. That in turn makes downstream usage/handling more consistent.
